article.description:
Even down by 13 points in the second half, the
Los Angeles Sparks didn't panic. They rarely do.
article.headline: Sparks silence Rockers in final minutes
article.linkText: Strong second half sparks Leslie, L.A. over Rockers
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Even down by 13 points in the second half, the Los Angeles Sparks didn't panic. They rarely do. Lisa Leslie scored 14 points after halftime and the Sparks rallied for a 79-71 win Tuesday night over Cleveland, spoiling the Rockers' WNBA season opener and a visit from LeBron James. Leslie finished with 20 points and 12 rebounds, Tamecka Dixon had 18 points and Nikki Teasley 16 for the two-time defending champion Sparks, who held the Rockers scoreless over the final 3:08. "We showed a lot of poise getting back in the game,'' Leslie said. "That comes from playing together and having confidence in one another.'' Los Angeles trailed 46-33 with 17:58 left, but with Dixon scoring from the outside and Leslie powering inside for easy baskets, the Sparks came back with a 50-point second half. Betty Lennox scored 23 points in her debut for Cleveland but she couldn't stop the Rockers from losing their 10th straight at Gund Arena. Penny Taylor added 17 points for Cleveland, which missed its final four shots. "The most disturbing thing, is we gave up 19 points over the last five minutes,'' Rockers coach Dan Hughes said. "That means we're giving up a lot of layups. We let Leslie have it (the ball) too low, too many times.'' Lennox, acquired by the Rockers last month in the league's dispersal draft, scored 17 points in the first half as the Rockers built their lead before a crowd of 14,061, including high school star and Cavalier-to-be James. But the Sparks kept chipping away and tied the game at 66 with 3:38 left on Mwadi Mabika's basket. Lennox countered with a 3-pointer for Cleveland, but after Teasley hit a 3, Leslie's two free throws gave Los Angeles a 73-71 lead -- their first since 19-17 -- with 2:05 to go. Cleveland missed two straight field goal tries and Leslie put back her own miss underneath to make it 75-71 with 1:27 remaining. Following a turnover, Dixon scored on a layup to put the Sparks up by 6 and put the Rockers away. "I just missed shots in the second half,'' Lennox said. "There was just no extra pressure, I just missed.'' The Sparks were leading 19-17 when Leslie picked up her third personal foul with 8:06 left in the first half. With Leslie on the bench, Lennox scored 10 points as the Rockers went on a 20-10 run to take a 39-29 lead at the break. Lennox scored Cleveland's final six points in the half, hitting a 3-pointer with 1.1 seconds to play. "Betty never met a shot she didn't like,'' Leslie said of Lennox, who played for Minnesota and Miami last season. Game notes
James, wearing a Cavaliers' No. 34 throwback jersey, watched the game from Cavs owner Gordon Gund's private suite. ... Rockers G Merlakia Jones sang the national anthem. ... The Sparks, who were a league-best 13-3 on the road last season, will play their first four games outside Los Angeles. ... Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper improved 96-18 in his WNBA coaching career. ... The Rockers were just 4-12 at home last season. ... Cleveland made its one and only national TV appearance this season. Los Angeles is scheduled to be on 18 times. ... Cooper decided not to play center Jennifer Gillom, the league's second-leading all-time scorer.
